<BaseLayout
  breadcrumbs={[{ name: 'Home', url: '/' }, { name: 'Encapsulated Crawl Space Dehumidifier', url: '/encapsulated-crawl-space-dehumidifier-raleigh-nc' }]}
  title="Encapsulated Crawl Space Dehumidifier Raleigh NC | Triangle Dehumidifiers"
  description="Encapsulation alone doesn't control humidity. We install sealed crawl space dehumidifiers in Raleigh, NC to maintain ~50% Relative Humidity (RH) and help prevent mold."
  canonical="/encapsulated-crawl-space-dehumidifier-raleigh-nc"
  heroImage="/images/encapsulated-crawl-space-raleigh-nc.webp"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="svc-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Encapsulated Crawl Space Dehumidifier Installation in Raleigh, NC</h1>
      <span class="svc-hero__direct"
        >Encapsulation alone does not control humidity. We install properly sized dehumidifiers to
        maintain ~50% Relative Humidity (RH) inside sealed crawl spaces.</span
      >
      <p class="svc-hero__sub">
        Even professionally encapsulated crawl spaces in Raleigh can exceed 60% RH without active
        humidity removal. A sealed space can trap humidity unless it is mechanically removed.
      </p>
      <p class="svc-hero__sub" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
        We inspect, size, install, and verify humidity control performance.
      </p>
      <div class="svc-hero__actions">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-green">Request Crawl Space Inspection</a>
        <a href="tel:9198670580" class="btn btn-secondary" aria-label="Call Triangle Dehumidifiers at (919) 867-0580">Call (919) 867-0580</a>
        <a href="sms:9198670580" class="btn btn-secondary" aria-label="Text Triangle Dehumidifiers at (919) 867-0580">Text (919) 867-0580</a>
      </div>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem; color:#4a5a6a; margin-top:0.75rem;">
        Serving Raleigh, Holly Springs, Cary, Apex, Fuquay-Varina, and the surrounding Triangle
        region.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 1 -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="svc-split">
        <div>
          <h2>Do Encapsulated Crawl Spaces Still Need a Dehumidifier?</h2>
          <span class="answer-first"
            >Yes. Encapsulation reduces moisture infiltration but does not remove humidity. A sealed
            crawl space requires active moisture control to maintain safe RH levels. A dehumidifier
            is the most effective solution.</span
          >
          <p>
            Encapsulation is an important first step — it reduces ground moisture intrusion and
            blocks soil vapor. But sealing the space does not regulate Relative Humidity. Moisture
            in the air still enters through foundation walls, seasonal air leakage, and diffusion
            through the liner itself.
          </p>
          <p>
            In Raleigh's humid climate, summer exterior Relative Humidity (RH) often exceeds 80%,
            increasing moisture load even in sealed systems. Without a dehumidifier, that moisture
            load has nowhere to go — RH can build until condensation forms. Eventually, mold becomes
            active on wood framing, HVAC equipment and ductwork, even behind foundation insulation
            and under a clean vapor barrier.
          </p>
          <p>
            Mold activates above 65% RH. The target range for a sealed crawl space is 45–50% Relative
            Humidity (RH) — maintained continuously by a properly sized dehumidifier.
          </p>
          <div class="icon-cards">
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#1a6fa8" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M7 16.3c2.2 0 4-1.83 4-4.05 0-1.16-.57-2.26-1.71-3.19S7.29 6.75 7 5.3c-.29 1.45-1.14 2.84-2.29 3.76S3 11.1 3 12.25c0 2.22 1.8 4.05 4 4.05z"/><path d="M12.56 6.6A10.97 10.97 0 0 0 14 3.02c.5 2.5 2 4.9 4 6.5s3 3.5 3 5.5a6.98 6.98 0 0 1-11.91 4.97"/></svg></span>
              <div>
                <strong>Moisture Through Foundation Walls</strong>
                <p>
                  Moisture can migrate through sections of concrete and block foundation walls
                  regardless of encapsulation
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#4f7d2a" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M8 2v4"/><path d="M16 2v4"/><rect width="18" height="18" x="3" y="4" rx="2"/><path d="M3 10h18"/></svg></span>
              <div>
                <strong>Seasonal Humidity Spikes</strong>
                <p>
                  NC summers regularly push exterior RH above 80% — sealed spaces absorb this load
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#4f7d2a" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M21 12a9 9 0 0 0-9-9 9.75 9.75 0 0 0-6.74 2.74L3 8"/><path d="M3 3v5h5"/><path d="M3 12a9 9 0 0 0 9 9 9.75 9.75 0 0 0 6.74-2.74L21 16"/><path d="M16 16h5v5"/></svg></span>
              <div>
                <strong>Air Leakage & Stack Effect Pressure</strong>
                <p>
                  Air movement caused by pressure differences and the stack effect pulls humid air
                  into the crawl space. In a sealed system, that moisture has limited escape paths,
                  allowing RH to gradually rise.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc-split__image" style="padding-top:0;">
          <img
            src="/images/encapsulated-crawl-space-raleigh-nc.webp"
            alt="Encapsulated crawl space with vapor barrier in Raleigh NC"
            width="780"
            height="320"
            fetchpriority="high"
            style="width:100%;height:320px;object-fit:cover;border-radius:var(--radius-md);display:block;"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 2 -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:780px;">
      <h2>What Is the Ideal Relative Humidity (RH) for a Sealed Crawl Space?</h2>
      <span class="answer-first"
        >Most encapsulated crawl spaces should be maintained between 45–50% Relative Humidity (RH) to
        reduce mold risk and protect wood framing.</span
      >
      <p>
        At 45–50% RH, mold cannot sustain growth on wood surfaces — even if spores are present. Mold
        growth risk increases rapidly above 65% RH, which is why we target a stable 45–50% range.
        This range also protects subflooring from moisture-related swelling, cupping, and
        delamination, and prevents condensation from forming on HVAC ductwork routed through the
        crawl space.
      </p>
      <p>
        Long-term structural health depends on consistent humidity control. Wood framing held at
        safe moisture content levels resists decay, maintains dimensional stability, and avoids the
        conditions that lead to costly repairs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SECTION 3 -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="svc-split">
        <div>
          <h2>How We Size Dehumidifiers for Encapsulated Crawl Spaces</h2>
          <span class="answer-first"
            >Proper sizing is based on crawl space volume, moisture load, and air exchange — not
            square footage alone.</span
          >
          <p>
            Sealed crawl spaces behave differently than vented ones. Lower air exchange rates mean
            moisture accumulates more slowly — but also means a correctly sized unit is critical.
            Undersized units run continuously without reaching target RH. Oversized units
            short-cycle and waste energy.
          </p>
          <p>
            We routinely work with 12-mil and 20-mil encapsulation systems and account for liner
            integrity when evaluating moisture load.
          </p>
          <div class="svc-steps">
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">1</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Calculate Crawl Space Volume</h3>
                <p>
                  Square footage and ceiling height determine total air volume the system must
                  control.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">2</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Assess Moisture Load</h3>
                <p>
                  Foundation wall type, soil conditions, and vapor barrier quality — including
                  12-mil and 20-mil systems — affect total moisture contribution.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">3</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Consider Air Exchange Rate</h3>
                <p>
                  Sealed systems have lower infiltration — we account for this when selecting unit
                  capacity.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">4</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Install Continuous Drainage</h3>
                <p>
                  No bucket systems. Dedicated drain line or condensate pump required for unattended
                  operation.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">5</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Verify Target RH at 45–50%</h3>
                <p>
                  System tested and programmed before we leave. Digital hygrometer installed for
                  ongoing monitoring.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc-split__image" style="padding-top:0;">
          <img
            src="/images/hvac-tech-measuring-humidity-encapsulated-crawl-space.webp"
